rollups will put all transaction data in the EIP-4844 blobs, then publish KZG commitments of the data (basically a signature) in the smart contracts in the EVM execution environment. for validity or fraud proofs, verifiers will submit all data which can be verified with KZG.

there's no change to security for rollups - it's about switching where rollup data is stored. today, rollups store  data in "calldata" which is in the same fee market as everything else in ethereum. EIP-4844 creates "blobs" that have their own fee market (lower cost).

Excited to share Coinbase's contributions to EIP-4844, an upcoming improvement to Ethereum that will scale layer 2 rollups, increasing transaction throughput and decreasing fees 10-100x

https://www.coinbase.com/blog/supporting-eip-4844-reducing-fees-for-ethereum-layer-2-rollups

Today, transaction fees for using Ethereum are still too high. We want to bring our over 100 million existing customers and the rest of the world into the cryptoeconomy, and in order to do that, we must make it cheap and easy for users to use crypto at scale.

EIP-4844 lowers fees by introducing a new transaction type to Ethereum that accepts ephemeral “blobs” of data, which are purpose built for storing rollup data. With this change in place, we expect gas fees on layer 2 rollups to decrease by 10-100x.

In May of this year, we got together with OPLabs and the EF and began collaborating to specify, implement, and test EIP-4844. We’re dedicating significant engineering resources to the effort and thanks to the teams’ collective effort, we’ve made a huge amount of progress.

We now have a full specification for the execution and consensus clients, working implementations in the Prysm and Geth clients, nearly complete preparations for the KZG ceremony, and a launched Devnet v1. And we’re excited to launch Devnet v2 in time for Devcon next week!

Given how important reducing transaction fees and increasing throughput is to bring the next billion users into the cryptoeconomy, we believe that the sooner EIP-4844 can safely be deployed to mainnet, the better.
Whether you’re a rollup, an exchange, or just an interested individual, if you’re interested in supporting the effort, you can learn more and get involved at eip4844.com.

IMO the easiest way to think about this is that choosing Polygon PoS is the same as choosing any other PoS L1, where you're relying on the security of the chain's validator set. 

This is a very different security model than an L2 which inherits the security of its base layer (e.g. Ethereum L1)

Optimism, Arbitrum, Fuel are “optimistic” rollups that inherit the security of Etheruem

zkSync, Polygon Hermez, Scroll are zkEVM rollups that inherit the security of Ethereum (all pre-mainnet)

same as security - L2s inherit the decentralization properties of their base layer whereas L1s have their own decentralization properties

e.g. Optimism/Arbitrum have the same censorship resistance guarantees as Ethereum whereas Polygon PoS censorship resistance is determined by its validator set

that said, I think generic “decentralization” is way too broad to really discuss. better to probe more specifically about characteristics you care about.

for instance, Optimism/Arbitrum have centralized sequencers today…but you can submit a transaction on L1 to force inclusion.

I’d also note that the L2s I’m discussing all have some level of “training wheels” on them, which means they are pointed in a long term direction where they’ll inherit L1 characteristics even more

That’s very different than Polygon PoS which long term will still be its own L1 with its own characteristics

I am supportive of more folks experimenting at L1 and think what Celestia is doing is a meaningful contribution to the space!

From my conversations with a number of folks, they are taking a pretty different approach re: data availability vs. danksharding. The best analogy is probably DPOS vs. POS.

In Celestia, you'll have a smaller number of "full nodes" that will store all the data and then enable other nodes to peer off them. This will be a smaller number of nodes (max 100s), who participate in Tendermint, and have higher hardware requirements.

In danksharding, the aim is to maintain the hundreds of thousands of validators and thousands or tens of thousands of nodes and have a homogenous topology where all nodes are participating in the same way.

these architectures have different tradeoffs around decentralization, but I think both are interesting and worth exploring. 

that said, I think the core offerings will overtime trend towards relative similarity and that the network effects around Ethereum and rollups will be hard to overcome.
